        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_unknown_04_page02.jpg"/>
                <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
                <opener>
                    <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                        <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                        <date when="1816-08-04"/></dateline>
                    <salute>
                        <persName>
                            <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                        </persName>
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#MillJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Mill</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RicaD1"></persName>M.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Ricardo</persName> hold<lb/>
                    a doctrine about Rewards w<del>y</del> no <choice><orig>re-<lb/>
                        ward</orig><reg>reward</reg></choice> can be given to one person<lb/>
                    without injury to some other<lb/>
                    person or class of persons - by <hi rend="underline"><choice><orig>inju<lb/>
                        ry</orig><reg>injury</reg></choice></hi> here includes the idea of <choice><orig>restrain<lb/>
                            -ing</orig><reg>restraining</reg></choice> their liberty - diminishing their<lb/>
                    privileges - or enjoyments -<lb/>
                    Perhaps I should express the doctrine<lb/>
                    more exactly by saying that they<lb/>
                    expect that you cannot give a <choice><orig>re
                        -ward</orig><reg>reward</reg></choice> to one person without it's<lb/>
                    being at the expense of some other or other<lb/>
                   <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_unknown_04_page01.jpg"/> 
                    - I argued this point with Ricardo &amp; he<lb/>
                    gave up - but I never had an opportunity<lb/>
                    of stating any argument to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MillJ1">Mill</persName> - What do<lb/>
                    you think of this doctrine? - Take a crown of<lb/>
                    parsley for instance as your reward.<lb/></p>
                    
                <p> When you have time to think<lb/>
                    for me will you next consider my D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi><lb/>
                    friend whether <hi rend="underline">travelling</hi> &amp; <hi rend="underline">The Travellers</hi><lb/>
                    would make a good subject for a<lb/>
                    story for me to write - the rage for travelling<lb/>
                    you know is prevalent - <hi rend="underline"></hi>Eyes</hi> &amp; no <hi rend="underline">Eyes</hi>-<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">Ears and no ears</hi> - The affectation - The<lb/>
                    ignorance - The ill humor - The national<lb/>
                    &amp; personal prejudices <add>pulling different ways</add> of a party of travellers<lb/>
                    might be drawn - the advantages &amp; <choice><orig>disadvan<lb/>
                        -tages</orig><reg>disadvantages</reg></choice> to their country &amp; to their own happiness<lb/>
                    must be shown - You will see in a moment all<lb/>
                    that can be made of the subject - w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> you advise me to<lb/>
                    follow or abandon it - <hi rend="underline">I</hi> will <hi rend="underline">not</hi><hi rend="underline">begin</hi>till  I have y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi><hi rend="underline">answer</hi><lb/>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p><!--A postscript goes here, outside the <closer>. --></p>
                </postscript>
                <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
